    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-08-18T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-08-18T23:00:00-05:00" n="497"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d497">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/9528: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-19T12:00:00+08:00"
                            >August 19, 1937—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received August 20—6:45
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>467. The informant cited in Embassy’s 460, August 18, noon,<note n="44"
                        xml:id="d497fn44">Not printed; the Soviet Military Attaché in China was
                        cited.</note> states that Chinese Communist troops are already in Suiyuan
                    moving toward the Chahar front for guerilla acting [<hi rend="italic"
                        >warfare?</hi>], thus confirming similar information reported in our 404,
                    August 12, 9 a.m.</p>
                <p>2. Further word that Chinese Communists are joining with the Government to form a
                    popular front has been received from an official <pb facs="0454" n="447"
                        xml:id="pg_447"/> who recently attended a social affair given by Chiang
                    Kai-shek at which were present at one table Feng Yu Hsiang, Yen Hsi Shan, Pai
                    Chung Hsi, Chu Teh, Mao Tze Tung and Chou En Lai.<note n="45" xml:id="d497fn45"
                        >The last three were Chinese Communist leaders.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
